---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
    title="Medical Expenditure Panel Survey (MEPS) - Claire Nyquist"
    description="Interactive data visualizations exploring healthcare utilization, expenditures, and insurance coverage from the Medical Expenditure Panel Survey (MEPS) conducted by AHRQ."
>
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8 lg:max-w-[95vw]">
        <!-- Hero Section -->
        <div class="text-center mb-4 md:mb-6">
            <h1
                class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-6xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 md:mb-6"
            >
                Medical Expenditure Panel Survey
            </h1>
            <p
                class="text-lg sm:text-xl text-gray-600 max-w-3xl mx-auto leading-relaxed px-4"
            >
                Exploring U.S. healthcare utilization, expenditures, and
                insurance coverage.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Heatmap Visualization -->
        <div class="mb-6">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border overflow-hidden">
                <!-- Year Slider -->
                <div
                    class="flex items-center justify-center gap-3 py-3 px-4 border-b bg-gray-50"
                >
                    <label
                        for="year-slider"
                        class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-600">Year</label
                    >
                    <button
                        id="year-play"
                        type="button"
                        class="w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center rounded-full border border-gray-300 bg-white hover:bg-gray-100 text-gray-600 transition-colors"
                        aria-label="Play through years"
                    >
                        <svg id="play-icon" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" class="w-4 h-4">
                            <path d="M6.3 2.84A1.5 1.5 0 004 4.11v11.78a1.5 1.5 0 002.3 1.27l9.344-5.891a1.5 1.5 0 000-2.538L6.3 2.84z" />
                        </svg>
                        <svg id="pause-icon" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" class="w-4 h-4 hidden">
                            <path d="M5.75 3a.75.75 0 00-.75.75v12.5c0 .414.336.75.75.75h1.5a.75.75 0 00.75-.75V3.75A.75.75 0 007.25 3h-1.5zM12.75 3a.75.75 0 00-.75.75v12.5c0 .414.336.75.75.75h1.5a.75.75 0 00.75-.75V3.75a.75.75 0 00-.75-.75h-1.5z" />
                        </svg>
                    </button>
                    <input
                        type="range"
                        id="year-slider"
                        min="0"
                        max="4"
                        value="4"
                        step="1"
                        class="w-40 sm:w-56 accent-indigo-600 cursor-pointer"
                    />
                    <span
                        id="year-display"
                        class="text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700 tabular-nums w-12 text-center"
                        >2022</span
                    >
                </div>

                <!-- Plotly Heatmap Container -->
                <div class="p-2 sm:p-4">
                    <div id="meps-heatmap" style="width:100%;"></div>
                </div>

                <!-- Citation -->
                <div
                    class="px-4 pb-4 text-xs text-gray-500 border-t bg-gray-50"
                >
                    <p class="mt-2">
                        <strong>Data Source:</strong> Agency for Healthcare Research
                        and Quality. Medical Expenditure Panel Survey <span
                            id="citation-year">2022</span
                        >.
                        <a
                            href="https://meps.ahrq.gov/mepsweb/"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 break-words"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener">https://meps.ahrq.gov/mepsweb/</a
                        >
                    </p>
                    <p class="mt-1">
                        <strong>Note:</strong> MEPS does not include state-level identifiers
                        for confidentiality. Regional data (Northeast, Midwest, South,
                        West) is used instead. Values are normalized within each variable
                        for comparison.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Description -->
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
            <p class="text-base sm:text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed px-4">
                The <a
                    href="https://meps.ahrq.gov/mepsweb/"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener">Medical Expenditure Panel Survey (MEPS)</a
                > is conducted by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ).
                It provides nationally representative data on health care use, expenditures,
                sources of payment, and insurance coverage for the U.S. civilian noninstitutionalized
                population.
            </p>
            <p
                class="text-base sm:text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-4 px-4"
            >
                The heatmap above uses normalized values to allow comparison
                across variables with different scales. Each row is
                independently normalized using min-max scaling:
                (value&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;min)&nbsp;/&nbsp;(max&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;min),
                where min and max are the smallest and largest values within
                that row. This maps every variable to a 0&ndash;1 range, where 0
                represents the lowest value across all region-age groups and 1
                represents the highest. Hover over any cell to see the original
                value.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Methodology -->
        <div class="mt-12 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Methodology
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                All estimates are produced using the
                <a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/survey/"
                   class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800"
                   target="_blank" rel="noopener">R survey package</a>
                following
                <a href="https://meps.ahrq.gov/mepsweb/survey_comp/standard_errors.jsp"
                   class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800"
                   target="_blank" rel="noopener">AHRQ-recommended methods</a>
                for complex survey data. Each year is analyzed independently
                as a cross-sectional snapshot of the U.S. civilian noninstitutionalized
                population.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-4 mb-1">Survey Weights</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                MEPS oversamples certain populations&mdash;including low-income
                families, racial and ethnic minorities, and the elderly&mdash;to
                ensure they are adequately represented. Each observation carries
                a person-level final weight (e.g., PERWT22F for 2022) that
                adjusts for this oversampling as well as survey nonresponse and
                post-stratification to Census population totals. All means shown
                in the heatmap are weighted, so they represent the full
                U.S. population, not just the ~30,000 survey respondents.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-4 mb-1">Variance Estimation</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                Because MEPS uses a stratified, multi-stage cluster design,
                standard formulas for simple random samples would understate
                the true uncertainty. This analysis specifies the stratum
                (VARSTR) and primary sampling unit (VARPSU) variables and uses
                Taylor-series linearization to produce correct standard errors.
                In practical terms, this means the confidence intervals properly
                reflect the fact that people within the same geographic cluster
                tend to be more similar to each other than to the population at
                large.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-4 mb-1">Domain (Subgroup) Analysis</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                When computing estimates for subgroups (e.g., adults age 45&ndash;64
                in the South), the full survey design is preserved rather than
                subsetting the data first. This is critical: dropping
                observations outside the subgroup would remove information the
                variance estimator needs, producing standard errors that are
                too small. The R survey package&rsquo;s <code class="text-xs bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">subset()</code>
                method on a <code class="text-xs bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">svydesign</code>
                object handles this correctly by zeroing out weights for
                out-of-domain observations while retaining them in the
                design structure.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-4 mb-1">Expenditures Are in Nominal Dollars</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                Dollar amounts shown in the heatmap (Mean Total Expenditure
                and Mean Out-of-Pocket) are reported in nominal
                dollars for each survey year&mdash;that is, they
                reflect the prices that prevailed in that year without
                adjustment for inflation. Between 2018 and 2022, the
                <a href="https://data.bls.gov/timeseries/CUUR0000SAM"
                   class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800"
                   target="_blank" rel="noopener">CPI for Medical Care</a>
                rose roughly 10&ndash;12%, meaning that a portion of any
                increase in expenditures across years reflects higher prices
                rather than greater utilization of services. Because of this,
                direct year-over-year comparison of the raw dollar values in
                the tooltip can overstate real spending growth. To make
                expenditures comparable across time, they would need to be
                deflated to a common base year using an appropriate price
                index such as the CPI for Medical Care or the Personal
                Consumption Expenditures (PCE) Health price index. The
                heatmap&rsquo;s color scale is not affected by this issue:
                normalization is performed independently within each year,
                so the color pattern shows relative differences between
                region-age groups for a given year, not absolute dollar
                comparisons across years.
            </p>

            <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-4 mb-1">No Pooling Across Years</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Each survey year is analyzed as a standalone cross-section.
                The data are not pooled across years, so no weight adjustment
                (dividing by the number of pooled years) is necessary. This
                approach is appropriate for examining how population-level
                estimates change over time but means that rarer conditions or
                smaller subgroups may exhibit more year-to-year volatility
                than they would in a pooled multi-year analysis.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Data Sources -->
        <div class="mt-12 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Data Sources
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality. (2024). Medical
                Expenditure Panel Survey. [Data set]. U.S. Department of Health
                and Human Services. <a
                    href="https://meps.ahrq.gov/mepsweb/"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 break-words"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener">https://meps.ahrq.gov/mepsweb/</a
                >
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                For accessing MEPS data in R, see the <a
                    href="https://github.com/e-mitchell/meps_r_pkg"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener">MEPS R Package</a
                > maintained by AHRQ.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">
                R Core Team. (2024). R: A Language and Environment for
                Statistical Computing. R Foundation for Statistical Computing,
                Vienna, Austria. <a
                    href="https://www.R-project.org/"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 break-words"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener">https://www.R-project.org/</a>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Lumley, T. (2004). Analysis of Complex Survey Samples.
                <em>Journal of Statistical Software</em>, 9(8), 1&ndash;19.
                R package version 4.4. <a
                    href="https://cran.r-project.org/package=survey"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800 break-words"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener">https://cran.r-project.org/package=survey</a>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Lexend font for visualization -->
